This is one of the earlier and smaller of the nntk vetehes, of which many different kinds grow in Western Canada. Its stems are slender, rather weak, branched at the base, and from three to eight inches high. The flower clusters resemble clover-heads, while the leaves are reminiscent of those of the true veteh but are without the tendril. The pods are short, thick, and hairy.

The Purple Milk Vetch is common over a wide area, growing in the open or on the edge of thickets, in a variety of soils. It likes some moisture, and, among the grass in low meadows, makes a thrifty growth lke that shown, almost natural size, in the picture; but the deep black loam of the prairie is for some reasou not congenial. It may be noticed, however, that, where the grading of a road through such soil has in places removed the top layer, exposing the hard, poor-looking subsoil, the Purple Milk Veteh is often one of the plants that quickly and mysteriously covers the naked earth with verdure. Jfow do plants, strangers to the immediate neighborhood, so promptly take possession? To attempt a full explanation would take many pages, and be beyond the scope of this little book. One is reminded of a sentence by Oliver Wendell Homes

“Nay, there are certain patches of ground, which, having lain neglected for a time, Nature, who always has her pockets full of seeds, and holes in all her pockets, has covered with lnmegry plebian growths, which fight for life with eael: other, until some of them get broad-leaved and succulent, and vou have a coarse vegetable tapestry which Raphael would not have disdained to spread over the foreground of his masterpiece.”
